{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":1183,"record_hash":"sha256:c5a114f80aa21ede1c2d4d0b8afeca21f0bac7d5a163013de1ac38bc8bfead38","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:22:51.446Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: f001f3\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 4170\nOutput:\n   380\t  HTTP routes / API / page rendering\n   381\t  GitHub public PR lookup\n   382\t  internal generation module\n   383\t  local repository cache\n   384\t  but-agentlog projection API\n   385\t```\n   386\t\n   387\tThe cleanest v1 implementation is a small Rust web app, likely Axum or similar,\n   388\tthat links the `but-agentlog` public/read projection API directly. That avoids\n   389\tNAPI, helper binaries, and service-to-service HTTP. It also keeps the filesystem\n   390\twork in the same runtime that owns the volume.\n   391\t\n   392\tThe internal generation function should be boring:\n   393\t\n   394\t```text\n   395\tgenerate_agent_trail(request: AgentTrailProjectionRequest)\n   396\t  -> AgentTrailProjectionResult\n   397\t```\n   398\t\n   399\tThe request should include:\n   400\t\n   401\t- `repoPath` or a future explicit GitMeta source handle\n   402\t- `metadataOid`\n   403\t- `pr`: Agent Trail host, GitHub repo id, owner, repo, PR number, base ref,\n   404\t  head ref, and head SHA\n   405\t- `limits`: max sessions, turns, records, bytes per record, total bytes, and\n   406\t  runtime deadline\n   407\t- `projectionVersion`\n   408\t\n   409\tThe response should include only the public projection and status/warning\n   410\tfields. It must not include raw session keys, raw turn keys, provider session\n   411\tids, filesystem paths, `source_record`, or hidden/system/developer messages.\n   412\t\n   413\tIf the project later chooses a Node/Next monolith for web ergonomics, then use\n   414\tGitButler's NAPI pattern with a dedicated Agent Trail package. GitButler already\n   415\thas a working NAPI shape:\n   416\t\n   417\t- `crates/but-api` marks Rust APIs with `#[but_api(napi)]`\n   418\t- `crates/but-napi` is a `cdylib` that links the generated exports\n   419\t- `packages/but-sdk` runs `@napi-rs/cli`, ships generated `index.js`,\n   420\t  `index.d.ts`, and platform `.node` artifacts\n   421\t\n   422\tIn that case, borrow the packaging pattern, not the broad\n[TRUNCATED]\ncan attach\n   827\t  persistent disks; default service filesystems are ephemeral\n   828\t  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks)).\n   829\t- Railway volumes mount read/write persistent storage into a service\n   830\t  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)).\n   831\t\n   832\tImplication: deploy the Agent Trail app as a long-lived container with a\n   833\tpersistent volume. Do not use Vercel/serverless for generation.\n   834\t\n   835\t### Rust / Node Boundary\n   836\t\n   837\tNAPI is the cleanest Rust-to-Node bridge only if the Agent Trail app is a Node\n   838\tweb process. A Rust web app can avoid the bridge entirely.\n   839\t\n   840\tRelevant findings:\n   841\t\n   842\t- Node-API is ABI-stable across Node versions, which makes it the right native\n   843\t  addon foundation\n   844\t  ([Node-API docs](https://nodejs.org/api/n-api.html)).\n   845\t- `napi-rs` can build Rust native addons and emit platform-suffixed `.node`\n   846\t  artifacts such as `index.darwin-x64.node`\n   847\t  ([napi-rs CLI](https://napi-rs.github.io/napi-rs/cli/)).\n   848\t- A helper binary is operationally simpler than NAPI in some deployments because\n   849\t  it isolates crashes and avoids native addon bundling, but it still requires\n   850\t  binary packaging, filesystem access, `git`, and a cache.\n   851\t- WASM/WASI is a bad fit. Node's WASI support is still marked experimental, and\n   852\t  Rust's base WASI target does not support process spawning. Agent Trail wants\n   853\t  real Git repository behavior, so WASM adds friction without removing the hard\n   854\t  dependency.\n   855\t\n   856\tImplication: prefer a Rust web app that links the projection API directly. If\n   857\tthe app must run on Node, prefer a dedicated `but-agenttrail-napi` package and\n   858\texternalize it from Next bundling.\n   859\t\n   860\t### Current Recommendation\n   861\t\n   862\tBuild this as one deployable Agent Trail app:\n   863\t\n   864\t- HTTP/API/page layer: URL replacement, GitHub PR lookup, public JSON contract,\n   865\t  status polling, snapshot route, and UI.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:22:51.446Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}